# Flutter / Dart “Senior” Standards

Build maintainable, modular Flutter code with strict typing and lifecycle safety.

## Architecture & separation of concerns

- Keep widget trees lean; extract logic into helpers/services/models when it improves clarity
- Avoid dumping unrelated code into one file; keep files focused and reasonably small

## Responsive UI (no hardcoded screens)

- Do **not** hardcode screen dimensions
- Prefer `LayoutBuilder`, `MediaQuery`, and flexible widgets (`Expanded`, `Flexible`) for sizing
- Use `SafeArea` where needed (notches, insets)
- Assume keyboard/overlays can change available height

## Lifecycle & memory safety

- Always `dispose()` resources you create (e.g. `TextEditingController`, `AnimationController`, `ScrollController`, `FocusNode`)
- For async work that updates UI or navigates: guard with `if (!mounted) return;`

## State & performance

- Do **not** trigger `setState` from within build/layout/paint phases
- Prefer `const` constructors where possible
- Minimize rebuilds: keep state local, avoid unnecessary listeners, and don’t rebuild large subtrees for small changes

## Strict typing & idiomatic Dart

- Avoid `dynamic` when a concrete model/type makes sense
- Keep null-safety explicit and idiomatic (`?`, `!`, `??`) and avoid unsafe casts
- Prefer clear, explicit types over ambiguous `var` when it improves readability/API contracts
